, "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "&alpha;-tubulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9800922274589539, "span": {"begin": 591, "end": 606}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7275"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "tubulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9903045296669006, "span": {"begin": 615, "end": 622}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Microtubules", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.3945448398590088, "span": {"begin": 658, "end": 670}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:55177", "55638", "51115", "151393"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "microtubule-associated proteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9115148186683655, "span": {"begin": 851, "end": 882}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:27352"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MAPs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8164458274841309, "span": {"begin": 884, "end": 888}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "microtubule regions", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5541329979896545, "span": {"begin": 979, "end": 998}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "microtubule code", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5138119459152222, "span": {"begin": 1022, "end": 1038}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "axons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5087767243385315, "span": {"begin": 1170, "end": 1175}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "peripheral neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8604076504707336, "span": {"begin": 1338, "end": 1356}}], "text": "Microtubules consist of &alpha;- and &beta;-tubulin heterodimer subunits which assemble into protofilaments. These protofilaments further form a hollow cylinder, the microtubule. Microtubules are polar structures due to the head-to-tail assembly of the tubulin heterodimers. The faster growing end of microtubules is called the plus end whereas the slower growing end is the minus end. The plus end is protected from rapid polymerisation by a GTP cap which is a ring of GTP-tubulin . However, when a new tubulin dimer is added to the plus end, GTP gets hydrolysed in the catalytic domain of &alpha;-tubulin and the tubulin subunit gets non-exchangeable. [1] Microtubules continuously undergo de- and repolymerization which is summarized as &ldquo;microtubule dynamic instability&rdquo;. [2] Microtubules are also stabilized by different proteins like microtubule-associated proteins (MAPs). Microtubule-related proteins often have preferential affinity for specifically modified microtubule regions, which is known as the microtubule code, including post-translational modifications like acetylation, detyrosination or polyamination. [1, 3] Furthermore, microtubules in axons exhibit specific orientation with the plus end pointing away from the soma whereas dendrites show mixed orientation of microtubules. [3] Due to the morphology of peripheral neurons possessing processes that can reach a length of more than one meter, an intact microtubule network is indispensable to ensure the supply of even the most distant parts of the neurites. [4]", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:44:17 +0000 2026"}